<h1>Smoked French Dip</h1>
<div class="time">Estimated Time to Completion: 5–6 hours</div>

<h2>Equipment</h2>
<ul>
<li>Smoker (pellet smoker recommended)</li>
<li>Meat thermometer</li>
<li>Foil pan or small roasting pan</li>
<li>Aluminum foil</li>
<li>Tongs</li>
</ul>

<h2>Ingredients</h2>
<ul>
<li>3–4 lb chuck roast</li>
<li>1 tbsp olive oil</li>
<li>Salt</li>
<li>Black pepper</li>
<li>1 tsp garlic powder</li>
<li>1 tsp onion powder</li>
</ul>

<h2>Au Jus / Braising Liquid</h2>
<ul>
<li>2 cups beef broth</li>
<li>1 tbsp Worcestershire sauce</li>
<li>3 cloves garlic, smashed</li>
<li>1 tsp onion powder</li>
<li>½ tsp black pepper</li>
</ul>

<h2>For Serving</h2>
<ul>
<li>Hoagie rolls or French rolls</li>
<li>Provolone cheese (optional)</li>
</ul>

<h2>How To</h2>
<ol>
<li>Preheat smoker: Set smoker to 250°F.</li>
<li>Season the beef: Rub chuck roast with olive oil. Season with salt, pepper, garlic powder, and onion powder.</li>
<li>Smoke: Place roast directly on smoker grate and smoke about 3 hours until internal temp reaches 160–165°F.</li>
<li>Braise: Place roast in a foil pan. Add beef broth, Worcestershire, garlic, onion powder, and pepper. Cover tightly with foil.</li>
<li>Return to smoker and cook another 2–3 hours until internal temperature reaches 200–205°F and beef is tender.</li>
<li>Rest: Let rest 15–20 minutes.</li>
<li>Slice or shred the beef.</li>
<li>Serve: Pile beef onto rolls, add provolone if desired, and serve with the au jus from the pan for dipping.</li>
</ol>

